{
  "text": "An ANN is trained by a collection of modeled signatures and estimates the linewidth of the L/S pattern according to experimental signatures. However, when an ANN has an excessive number of input terminals, its architecture becomes complicated and it tends to become instable, resulting in it being impractical for implementation in the semiconductor manufacturing process [CITATION_1] - [CITATION_2] . A radial basis function network (RBFN), an expanded version of the ANN, is an algorithm with the potential to solve the inverse problem in optical scatterometry. Compared with the ANN, the RBFN has architecture that is easy to implement [CITATION_3] . A Gaussian activation function is employed in the hidden layer to map the nonlinear input data. Consequently, the RBFN is sensitive to noisy data [CITATION_4] . Several papers have proposed and discussed the applications of the RBFN in various systems such as dipole antenna [CITATION_5] , robotic [CITATION_6] , earthquake prevention [CITATION_7] , and cardiology interval-valued data systems [CITATION_8] .",
  "correct_citation": {
